\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 88. T. alexandrinum} L.,{\i   Cent. Pl.}{\b  1}: 25 (1755). Annual; stems 40-70 cm, erect, branching, sparsely appressed-hairy. Leaflets 15-25 × 5-10 mm, oblong or lanceolate; free part of the stipules subulate, marginal hairs of the upper ones dilated at the base. Heads 15-20(-25) mm, ovoid or oblong-conical; peduncles up to 30 mm. Calyx hairy; tube obconical; teeth unequal, triangular-subulate, spinescent, the lowest 3-veined, at least at the base, about as long as the tube, others shorter, 1-veined. Corolla 8-10 mm, cream, about twice as long as the calyx. Apex of the mature legume slightly exserted, not concealed by the ring of hairs in the calyx-throat, which is devoid of a bilabiate callosity.{\i   Widely cultivated in the warmer parts of Europe and locally naturalized}. [Au Bu He Hs Hu Lu.]
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Long cultivated in N.E. Africa, possibly native in the E. Mediterranean region. Plants from S.E. Europe appear to belong to{\i   T. constantinopolitanum} ({\i  vide }{\b 90}) which is sometimes identified with {\i  T. alexandrinum} var.{\i   phleoides} (Boiss.) Boiss.
